        <introduction>
            <para>
                DigitalRise Animation supports Xbox LIVE Avatars. Avatars can be animated,
                animations can be cross-faded, avatar ragdolls can be automatically created, and much more.
            </para>
        </introduction>


        <section address="Avatars">
            <title>Xbox LIVE Avatars (Xbox 360 only)</title>
            <content>
                <alert class="warning">
                    <para>
                        The Xbox LIVE Avatar support in <legacyBold>DigitalRise Animation</legacyBold>
                        is newer and replaces the Xbox LIVE Avatar support in
                        <legacyBold>DigitalRise.Physics.Specialized</legacyBold>
                        (see <link xlink:href="3e1b091b-d795-4f67-a390-67648a3e5465" />).
                    </para>
                </alert>
                <para>
                    DigitalRise Animation also provides support for animating Xbox LIVE Avatars:
                    The class <codeEntityReference qualifyHint="false">T:DigitalRise.Animation.Character.AvatarPose</codeEntityReference>
                    describes the <codeEntityReference qualifyHint="false">T:DigitalRise.Animation.Character.SkeletonPose</codeEntityReference>
                    of an avatar as well as its
                    <externalLink>
                        <linkText>AvatarExpression</linkText>
                        <linkUri>http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/microsoft.xna.framework.gamerservices.avatarexpression.aspx</linkUri>
                    </externalLink>
                    (facial expression). <codeEntityReference qualifyHint="false">T:DigitalRise.Animation.Character.AvatarPose</codeEntityReference>
                    implements
                    <externalLink>
                        <linkText>IAvatarAnimation</linkText>
                        <linkUri>http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/microsoft.xna.framework.gamerservices.iavataranimation.aspx</linkUri>
                    </externalLink>
                    and therefore can be used directly with the XNA class for rendering.
                </para>
            </content>
        </section>


